## 1. Linux Basics

Understanding the foundational commands that every Linux user should know.

| Command | Description | Example Usage | Visual/Diagram Explanation |
|---------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------|
| `pwd` | Print Working Directory - shows current location | `pwd` | `[root] â†’ [home] â†’ [user] â†’ [YOU ARE HERE]` |
| `cd` | Change Directory - navigate filesystem | `cd /var/log`<br>`cd ..`<br>`cd ~` | `Current Dir â†’ cd /path â†’ New Dir` |
| `ls` | List directory contents | `ls -la`<br>`ls -lh` | `ğŸ“ Dir1  ğŸ“„ file.txt  ğŸ“ Dir2` |
| `man` | Manual pages - command documentation | `man ls`<br>`man grep` | `man [command] â†’ [DETAILED HELP PAGE]` |
| `whoami` | Display current username | `whoami` | `System â†’ [Current User: john]` |
| `hostname` | Show or set system hostname | `hostname`<br>`hostname -I` | `Computer Identity: myserver.local` |
| `uname` | Print system information | `uname -a`<br>`uname -r` | `Kernel â†’ Linux 5.15.0 [x86_64]` |
| `clear` | Clear terminal screen | `clear` or `Ctrl+L` | `[Cluttered Screen] â†’ clear â†’ [Clean Screen]` |
| `history` | Show command history | `history`<br>`history | grep ssh` | `1: ls â†’ 2: cd â†’ 3: pwd â†’ ... â†’ 100: history` |
| `exit` | Exit shell or terminal | `exit` | `[Terminal Session] â†’ exit â†’ [Closed]` |

### ğŸ’¡ Quick Tips
- Use `Tab` key for auto-completion
- `Ctrl+C` stops running commands
- `Ctrl+Z` suspends processes
- `!!` repeats last command
- `!$` uses last argument from previous command

### âš ï¸ Important Notes
- Linux is case-sensitive: `File.txt` â‰  `file.txt`
- Root directory is `/`, not `\` like Windows
- Hidden files start with `.` (dot)

