## 3. User & Permission Management

Control access, users, and security settings.

| Command | Description | Example Usage | Visual/Diagram Explanation |
|---------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------|
| `chmod` | Change file permissions | `chmod 755 script.sh`<br>`chmod +x file` | `rw- â†’ chmod 777 â†’ rwx (Full Access)` |
| `chown` | Change file owner | `chown user:group file.txt`<br>`chown -R www-data /var/www` | `ğŸ‘¤ OldOwner â†’ chown â†’ ğŸ‘¤ NewOwner` |
| `chgrp` | Change group ownership | `chgrp developers project/` | `ğŸ‘¥ Group1 â†’ chgrp â†’ ğŸ‘¥ Group2` |
| `useradd` | Create new user | `useradd -m -s /bin/bash john`<br>`useradd -G sudo alice` | `[System] â†’ useradd â†’ ğŸ‘¤ New User Created` |
| `userdel` | Delete user account | `userdel john`<br>`userdel -r alice` (remove home) | `ğŸ‘¤ User â†’ userdel â†’ [REMOVED]` |
| `usermod` | Modify user account | `usermod -aG docker john`<br>`usermod -L alice` (lock) | `ğŸ‘¤ User [Settings] â†’ usermod â†’ [Modified]` |
| `passwd` | Change user password | `passwd`<br>`passwd john` | `ğŸ”’ Old Pass â†’ passwd â†’ ğŸ”’ New Pass` |
| `su` | Switch user | `su - root`<br>`su john` | `ğŸ‘¤ Current â†’ su â†’ ğŸ‘¤ Target User` |
| `sudo` | Execute command as superuser | `sudo apt update`<br>`sudo -i` | `ğŸ‘¤ User â†’ sudo â†’ [ROOT PRIVILEGES] âš¡` |
| `groups` | Display user's groups | `groups`<br>`groups alice` | `ğŸ‘¤ User âˆˆ {sudo, www-data, developers}` |
| `id` | Print user/group IDs | `id`<br>`id -u john` | `UID=1000 GID=1000 groups=1000,27,999` |
| `whoami` | Print effective user name | `whoami` | `Current Session â†’ [john]` |
| `who` | Show logged in users | `who`<br>`who -b` (last boot) | `Terminal1: alice | Terminal2: bob` |
| `w` | Show who is logged in and activity | `w` | `USER  TTY  LOGIN@  IDLE  WHAT` |
| `last` | Show last logged in users | `last`<br>`last -n 10` | `Timeline: alice â†’ bob â†’ root [Login History]` |

### ğŸ”¢ Permission Numbers Explained

```
Permission Values:
r (read)    = 4
w (write)   = 2
x (execute) = 1

Common Combinations:
7 = rwx (4+2+1) Full access
6 = rw- (4+2)   Read + Write
5 = r-x (4+1)   Read + Execute
4 = r-- (4)     Read only
0 = ---         No access

Example: chmod 755 file
â”œâ”€ 7 (rwx) â†’ Owner has full control
â”œâ”€ 5 (r-x) â†’ Group can read and execute
â””â”€ 5 (r-x) â†’ Others can read and execute
```

### âš ï¸ Security Best Practices
- Never run `chmod 777` on production files
- Use `sudo` instead of logging in as root
- Regular users should NOT be in sudoers file unless necessary
- Always use strong passwords (`passwd`)
- Lock unused accounts: `usermod -L username`

### ğŸ¯ Cheat Sheet: Permissions

```bash
# Quick permission changes
chmod +x script.sh              # Make executable
chmod 644 *.txt                 # Standard file permissions
chmod 755 *.sh                  # Standard script permissions
chmod -R 750 /opt/app           # Recursive directory permissions

# Ownership changes
chown www-data:www-data -R /var/www
chown $(whoami) file.txt        # Take ownership
```

