## 4. System Monitoring & Processes

Monitor system health, manage processes, and optimize performance.

| Command | Description | Example Usage | Visual/Diagram Explanation |
|---------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------|
| `top` | Display dynamic real-time system processes | `top`<br>`top -u john` | `[CPU 45%] [RAM 2.3GB] [Processes List â†»]` |
| `htop` | Interactive process viewer (enhanced top) | `htop` | `Visual: â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ CPU | â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆ Memory [Interactive]` |
| `ps` | Report process status snapshot | `ps aux`<br>`ps -ef | grep nginx` | `PID  USER  %CPU  %MEM  COMMAND` |
| `pgrep` | Find process ID by name | `pgrep nginx`<br>`pgrep -u john` | `[Process Name] â†’ pgrep â†’ [PID: 1234]` |
| `pkill` | Kill processes by name | `pkill firefox`<br>`pkill -9 -u alice` | `[Process Name] â†’ pkill â†’ [TERMINATED]` |
| `kill` | Terminate process by PID | `kill 1234`<br>`kill -9 5678` | `PID 1234 â†’ kill -9 â†’ [FORCE KILLED]` |
| `killall` | Kill all processes by name | `killall chrome` | `[All chrome] â†’ killall â†’ [ALL KILLED]` |
| `jobs` | List background jobs | `jobs`<br>`jobs -l` | `[1]+ Running  script.sh &` |
| `bg` | Resume suspended job in background | `bg %1` | `[Suspended] â†’ bg â†’ [Running in Background]` |
| `fg` | Bring job to foreground | `fg %1` | `[Background] â†’ fg â†’ [Foreground Active]` |
| `nohup` | Run command immune to hangups | `nohup script.sh &` | `Terminal Closes â†’ [Process Continues] ğŸ›¡ï¸` |
| `nice` | Run process with modified priority | `nice -n 10 script.sh` | `Priority: -20 (high) â† 0 â†’ 19 (low)` |
| `renice` | Alter priority of running process | `renice -n 5 -p 1234` | `PID 1234 [Priority 0] â†’ renice â†’ [Priority 5]` |
| `free` | Display memory usage | `free -h`<br>`free -m` | `RAM: [â–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–ˆâ–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘] 4GB / 8GB Used` |
| `uptime` | Show system uptime and load | `uptime` | `â±ï¸ up 45 days, load: 0.5, 0.8, 1.2` |
| `vmstat` | Virtual memory statistics | `vmstat 1`<br>`vmstat -s` | `procs | memory | swap | io | system | cpu` |
| `iostat` | CPU and I/O statistics | `iostat -x 2` | `Device: sda | tps | kB_read/s | kB_wrtn/s` |
| `lsof` | List open files | `lsof -i :80`<br>`lsof -u john` | `[Port 80] â†’ lsof â†’ nginx (PID 1234)` |
| `systemctl` | Control systemd services | `systemctl start nginx`<br>`systemctl status ssh` | `Service â†’ [Stopped] â†’ start â†’ [Running] âœ“` |
| `service` | Run System V init script | `service apache2 restart` | `[Service] â†’ restart â†’ [Restarted]` |

### ğŸ“Š Process States Visual

```
Process Lifecycle:
[NEW] â†’ [READY] â†’ [RUNNING] â†’ [TERMINATED]
           â†“          â†‘
        [WAITING] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜

States:
R - Running or runnable
S - Sleeping (waiting for event)
D - Uninterruptible sleep (I/O)
Z - Zombie (terminated, waiting cleanup)
T - Stopped (suspended)
```

### ğŸ”§ Signal Types

```
Kill Signals:
SIGTERM (15) - Graceful termination (default)
SIGKILL (9)  - Force kill (cannot be caught)
SIGHUP (1)   - Hang up (restart service)
SIGSTOP (19) - Pause process

Usage:
kill -15 PID  â†’ Graceful shutdown
kill -9 PID   â†’ Force kill (use sparingly)
```

### ğŸ¯ Cheat Sheet: Process Management

```bash
# Find and kill process
ps aux | grep nginx
kill $(pgrep nginx)

# Run in background
./long_script.sh &
nohup ./script.sh > output.log 2>&1 &

# Monitor specific process
top -p $(pgrep apache2)
watch -n 1 'ps aux | grep python'

# System resource check
free -h && df -h && uptime
```

