## 5. Networking Commands

Network configuration, troubleshooting, and connectivity tools.

| Command | Description | Example Usage | Visual/Diagram Explanation |
|---------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------|
| `ping` | Test network connectivity | `ping google.com`<br>`ping -c 4 8.8.8.8` | `You â†’ [packets] â†’ â†’ â†’ Target â†’ [reply] â†’` |
| `ifconfig` | Configure network interface (deprecated) | `ifconfig eth0`<br>`ifconfig eth0 down` | `[NIC: eth0] IP: 192.168.1.10 MAC: aa:bb:cc` |
| `ip` | Show/manipulate routing, devices | `ip addr show`<br>`ip route`<br>`ip link set eth0 up` | `Interface â†’ [Status, IP, Routes, Config]` |
| `netstat` | Network statistics | `netstat -tuln`<br>`netstat -anp` | `Proto Local:Port Foreign:Port State PID` |
| `ss` | Socket statistics (faster netstat) | `ss -tuln`<br>`ss -s` | `[Listening Ports] [Established Connections]` |
| `curl` | Transfer data from/to server | `curl https://api.com`<br>`curl -O file.zip` | `Client â†’ [HTTP Request] â†’ Server â†’ [Response]` |
| `wget` | Download files from web | `wget https://file.com/data.zip`<br>`wget -c url` | `URL â†’ wget â†’ [ğŸ“¥ Downloaded File]` |
| `traceroute` | Trace packet route to host | `traceroute google.com` | `You â†’ Router1 â†’ Router2 â†’ ... â†’ Target` |
| `nslookup` | Query DNS servers | `nslookup google.com` | `Domain â†’ [DNS Query] â†’ IP: 142.250.X.X` |
| `dig` | DNS lookup utility | `dig google.com`<br>`dig +short example.com` | `Domain â†’ DNS â†’ [A Records, MX, NS, etc.]` |
| `host` | DNS lookup | `host google.com` | `google.com â†’ [172.217.X.X (A record)]` |
| `hostname` | Show or set system hostname | `hostname`<br>`hostname -I` | `System Name: myserver.local` |
| `arp` | Manipulate ARP cache | `arp -a` | `IP: 192.168.1.1 âŸ· MAC: aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff` |
| `route` | Show/manipulate IP routing table | `route -n` | `Destination â†’ Gateway â†’ Interface` |
| `nc` (netcat) | Network utility for reading/writing | `nc -l 8080`<br>`nc example.com 80` | `[Port Listener] âŸ· [Client Connection]` |
| `scp` | Secure copy between hosts | `scp file.txt user@host:/path/`<br>`scp -r dir/ user@host:` | `Local ğŸ“„ â†’ [SSH] â†’ Remote ğŸ“„` |
| `rsync` | Remote file synchronization | `rsync -avz /src/ user@host:/dest/` | `Source â†’ [Sync Î”] â†’ Destination (incremental)` |
| `ssh` | Secure shell remote login | `ssh user@hostname`<br>`ssh -i key.pem user@ip` | `Client â†’ [Encrypted Tunnel] â†’ Remote Server` |
| `telnet` | Connect to remote host (insecure) | `telnet example.com 80` | `Client â†’ [Unencrypted] â†’ Server âš ï¸` |
| `ftp` | File transfer protocol client | `ftp ftp.server.com` | `Local âŸ· [FTP] âŸ· Remote Server` |

### ğŸŒ OSI Model Reference

```
Layer 7: Application  â†’ HTTP, FTP, SSH, DNS
Layer 4: Transport    â†’ TCP, UDP (ports)
Layer 3: Network      â†’ IP, ICMP, routing
Layer 2: Data Link    â†’ MAC addresses, switches
Layer 1: Physical     â†’ Cables, signals

Troubleshooting Flow:
Physical (cables) â†’ IP config â†’ Routing â†’ DNS â†’ Application
```

### ğŸ“¡ Common Ports

```
20/21  - FTP
22     - SSH
23     - Telnet
25     - SMTP (Email)
53     - DNS
80     - HTTP
443    - HTTPS
3306   - MySQL
5432   - PostgreSQL
6379   - Redis
27017  - MongoDB
```

### ğŸ¯ Cheat Sheet: Networking

```bash
# Quick connectivity check
ping -c 3 8.8.8.8                    # Test internet
ip addr show                         # Show all IPs
ss -tuln | grep :80                  # Check if port 80 is listening

# Download files
wget -c https://example.com/file.zip # Resume download
curl -o output.html https://site.com # Save with custom name

# Remote operations
ssh user@server 'ls -la /var/log'    # Remote command
scp -r /local/dir user@host:/remote  # Copy directory
rsync -avz --progress src/ dest/     # Sync with progress

# DNS troubleshooting
dig +short example.com               # Quick IP lookup
nslookup example.com 8.8.8.8         # Use specific DNS server
```

